# Cosmic Ocean: Technical Architecture Document (V1)

*This document defines the strict software engineering blueprint for Cosmic Ocean. It acts as the final bridge between the Game Design Document and the actual implementation of the Vite + TypeScript + Three.js stack.*

---

## 1. Repository Structure

### 1.1 Rationale
A complex WebGL application requires rigorous separation of concerns. If UI logic leaks into the render loop, performance degrades. We separate the core engine (rendering, loop, events) from the world logic (boat, islands, water) and the DOM logic (Resume Mode).

### 1.2 Implementation Approach
We will use Vite with TypeScript. The source directory will be strictly domain-driven.

### 1.3 Folder Tree & Naming Conventions
```text
/src
  /assets           # Static files (GLBs, audio, textures)
    /models
    /audio
    /textures
  /core             # Engine singletons (App, Time, Sizes, Input)
  /world            # 3D Entities (Boat, Ocean, Island, Whale)
  /shaders          # GLSL files (.vert, .frag)
  /ui               # DOM manipulation (ResumeMode, Modals)
  /utils            # Math helpers, event emitters
  /styles           # CSS / SCSS
  main.ts           # Entry point
```
*   **Classes:** PascalCase (e.g., `BoatController.ts`).
*   **Instances/Utils:** camelCase (e.g., `mathUtils.ts`).
*   **Assets:** snake_case (e.g., `island_hub.glb`).

### 1.4 Risks & Mitigations
*   **Risk:** Circular dependencies between the `World` and `UI` layers.
*   **Mitigation:** Enforce a strict one-way data flow using the central Event System (e.g., `World` emits `onIslandApproached`, `UI` listens and updates the DOM).

