## 2. Application Architecture

### 2.1 Rationale
Passing `renderer`, `scene`, and `camera` down through 15 levels of constructors (prop drilling) leads to unmaintainable spaghetti code. We need global access without global variable pollution.

### 2.2 Implementation Approach
We will implement an **Explicit Dependency Injection** pattern. A single `App.ts` class initializes the core systems and orchestrates them, passing references via constructor parameters. We do not use global singletons.

### 2.3 Pseudocode
```typescript
class App {
    canvas: HTMLCanvasElement;
    scene: THREE.Scene;
    camera: Camera;
    renderer: Renderer;
    time: Time;
    sizes: Sizes;
    world: World;

    constructor(canvas: HTMLCanvasElement) {
        this.canvas = canvas;
        this.sizes = new Sizes();
        this.time = new Time();
        this.scene = new THREE.Scene();
        
        // Pass app instance via constructor injection
        this.camera = new Camera(this);
        this.renderer = new Renderer(this);
        this.world = new World(this);

        this.time.on('tick', () => this.update());
    }

    update() {
        this.camera.update();
        this.world.update();
        this.renderer.update();
    }
}
```

### 2.4 Risks & Mitigations
*   **Risk:** Deeply nested classes requiring too many constructor parameters.
*   **Mitigation:** Keep the hierarchy flat. Only core systems need the root `App` reference.

