## 3. Three.js Architecture

### 3.1 Rationale
To achieve the "AAA-feeling" miniature diorama aesthetic, we must hijack the standard WebGL render pipeline to inject post-processing (tilt-shift depth of field) while maintaining 60 FPS.

### 3.2 Implementation Approach
*   **Renderer:** `WebGLRenderer` with `antialias: true`, `outputColorSpace = SRGBColorSpace`, and `toneMapping = ACESFilmicToneMapping`.
*   **Camera System:** An `OrthographicCamera` locked at an isometric angle (`x: 10, y: 10, z: 10` looking at `0,0,0`). It uses a `GSAP` lerp function to strictly follow the Boat's `X` and `Z` coordinates, keeping the boat centered.
*   **Post-processing:** Standard Three.js rendering. We may add a subtle Bloom pass (`UnrealBloomPass`) if performance allows, but no Tilt-Shift depth of field in V1 to ensure maximum performance across all devices.
*   **Lighting:** `AmbientLight` (low intensity) + a single `DirectionalLight` pointing from the moon. Real-time shadows are **DISABLED** to save draw calls. All shadows are baked into Matcaps.

### 3.3 Pseudocode (Camera Follow)
```typescript
update() {
    const boatPosition = this.app.world.boat.mesh.position;
    
    // Smooth interpolation (lerp)
    this.targetPosition.x = THREE.MathUtils.lerp(this.targetPosition.x, boatPosition.x, 0.1);
    this.targetPosition.z = THREE.MathUtils.lerp(this.targetPosition.z, boatPosition.z, 0.1);
    
    // Maintain isometric offset
    this.instance.position.set(
        this.targetPosition.x + 10,
        10,
        this.targetPosition.z + 10
    );
    this.instance.lookAt(this.targetPosition);
}
```

### 3.4 Risks & Mitigations
*   **Risk:** `UnrealBloomPass` can still be heavy on extremely old mobile devices.
*   **Mitigation:** Listen to the `Sizes` class. If the device pixel ratio is high or frame rate drops, disable the Bloom pass.

