## 9. Resume Mode Architecture

### 9.1 Rationale
A 3D portfolio is useless if an impatient recruiter leaves after 5 seconds. We must offer a 2D escape hatch instantly.

### 9.2 Implementation Approach
A React-style (or Vanilla JS with template literals) DOM overlay sitting on top of the `<canvas>`. Controlled by a global state toggle.

### 9.3 Pseudocode
```typescript
class UIManager {
    isResumeMode = false;
    canvas = document.querySelector('canvas');
    resumeUI = document.querySelector('#resume-overlay');

    constructor(private app: App) {}

    init() {
        document.querySelector('#btn-resume').addEventListener('click', () => this.toggle());
    }

    toggle() {
        this.isResumeMode = !this.isResumeMode;
        
        if (this.isResumeMode) {
            // Pause 3D World (Saves Battery/CPU)
            this.app.time.pause();
            
            // Show UI
            this.resumeUI.classList.add('visible');
            this.canvas.style.filter = 'blur(10px) brightness(0.3)';
        } else {
            // Resume 3D World
            this.app.time.resume();
            
            // Hide UI
            this.resumeUI.classList.remove('visible');
            this.canvas.style.filter = 'none';
        }
    }
}
```

### 9.4 Risks & Mitigations
*   **Risk:** The 3D scene continues rendering in the background, causing the browser to freeze while the user reads the resume.
*   **Mitigation:** Explicitly pause the `requestAnimationFrame` loop when `isResumeMode === true`.

