## 10. Audio System

### 10.1 Rationale
Using raw HTML5 `<audio>` tags leads to overlapping, clipping, and auto-play policy failures.

### 10.2 Implementation Approach
We will use the **Howler.js** library to manage all audio. It uses the Web Audio API under the hood, allowing for spatial fading and seamless looping.

### 10.3 Pseudocode
```typescript
import { Howl } from 'howler';

class AudioSystem {
    ambient: Howl;
    
    init() {
        this.ambient = new Howl({
            src: ['/assets/audio/ocean_ambient.mp3'],
            loop: true,
            volume: 0.5
        });
        
        // Wait for first user interaction to bypass autoplay restrictions
        window.addEventListener('click', () => {
            if (!this.ambient.playing()) this.ambient.play();
        }, { once: true });
    }

    fadeForWhale() {
        this.ambient.fade(0.5, 0.0, 2000); // Fade out over 2 seconds
        setTimeout(() => this.ambient.fade(0.0, 0.5, 3000), 10000); // Fade back in
    }
}
```

### 10.4 Risks & Mitigations
*   **Risk:** Browsers block audio until the user interacts with the page.
*   **Mitigation:** Tie the `Howler.play()` initialization to the "Click to Start" button on the loading screen.

